<typeStatus id="54CB884EFF8BFFA6FF23FAA5FEBCFAB5" box="[197,256,1368,1394]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FE89FAA4FD63FAB4" authority="Yi &amp; Jin" authorityName="Yi &amp; Jin" box="[367,735,1369,1395]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Orientilimnesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FE89FAA4FDC8FAB5" box="[367,628,1369,1394]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Orientilimnesia sinica</emphasis>
Yi &amp; Jin
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2375785FF8BFFA6FD00FAA4FCFDFAB4" box="[742,833,1369,1395]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36A6567FF8BFFA6FF23FA82FA3EFA5D" box="[197,1410,1407,1434]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCF36ECFF8BFFA6FF23FA82FA3EFA5D" blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" box="[197,1410,1407,1434]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FF23FA82FEF0FA5E" bold="true" box="[197,332,1407,1433]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Etymology</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FEBDFA7DFE7BFA5E" box="[347,455,1408,1433]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FEBDFA7DFE7BFA5E" box="[347,455,1408,1433]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like mite from the oriental. “Orienti-”, from “Orientalis” in latin, means oriental.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36A6567FF8BFFA6FF23FA5BFBDBF8DB" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BCF36ECFF8BFFA6FF23FA5BFB78F9F3" blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FF23FA5BFE8BFA07" bold="true" box="[197,311,1446,1472]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Remarks</emphasis>
: The number and position of genital acetabula are used as characters for the diagnosis of genera and species of water mites (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B1DFF8BFFA6FE3DFA30FDDDFA20" author="Cook" box="[475,609,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" refString="Cook, D. R. (1974) Water mites genera and subgenera. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 21, 1 - 1858. Goldschmidt, T. (2004) Studies on Neotropical Limnesiidae Thor, 1910 Part III: Protolimnesiinae sensu K. Viets, 1953 (Acari, Actinedida, Hydrachnidia). Archiv fur Hydrobiologie, Supplement, 151, 69 - 123." type="journal article" year="1974">
Cook 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FDC2FA30FDDDFA20" box="[548,609,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1974.0">1974</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B1DFF8BFFA6FD8BFA30FD5FFA20" author="Barr" box="[621,739,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" refString="Barr, D. W. (1982) Comparative morphology of the genital acetabula of aquatic mites (Acari, Prostigmata): Hydrachnoidea, Eylaoidea, Hydryphantoidea and Lebertioidea. Journal of Natural History, 16, 147 - 160." type="journal article" year="1982">
Barr 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FD4FFA30FD5FFA20" box="[681,739,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).Within 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FCAAFA30FC61FA20" box="[844,989,1485,1511]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Limnesiidae</taxonomicName>
the number of acetabula is three pairs to many; their shape is round, oval, elongated or lobated; they are usually situated on genital flaps or plates (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B1DFF8BFFA6FF79F9E7FE9FF9F3" author="Cook" box="[159,291,1562,1588]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" refString="Cook, D. R. (1974) Water mites genera and subgenera. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 21, 1 - 1858. Goldschmidt, T. (2004) Studies on Neotropical Limnesiidae Thor, 1910 Part III: Protolimnesiinae sensu K. Viets, 1953 (Acari, Actinedida, Hydrachnidia). Archiv fur Hydrobiologie, Supplement, 151, 69 - 123." type="journal article" year="1974">
Cook 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FF01F9E7FE9FF9F3" box="[231,291,1562,1588]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1974.0">1974</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) but may also lay under genital flaps beside the gonopore (Goldschmidt 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FB9EF9E7FB04F9F3" box="[1144,1208,1562,1588]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="2004.0">2004</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCF36ECFF8BFFA6FF23F9BCFBDBF8DB" blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
Within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FEACF9BCFE60F99C" box="[330,476,1601,1627]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Limnesiidae</taxonomicName>
two species have elongated acetabula: 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FC49F9BCFAE6F99C" authority="Lundblad, 1953" authorityName="Lundblad" authorityYear="1953" box="[943,1370,1601,1627]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipora">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FC49F9BCFB2BF99D" box="[943,1175,1601,1626]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia longipora</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B1DFF8BFFA6FB79F9BCFAE6F99C" author="Lundblad" box="[1183,1370,1601,1627]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" refString="Lundblad, O. (1953) Die Hydracarinenfauna von Columbia. Arkiv for Zoologi (Ser. 2), 5, 435 - 585." type="journal article" year="1953">
Lundblad, 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FAF9F9BCFAE6F99C" box="[1311,1370,1601,1627]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1953.0">1953</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F367767CFF8BFFA6FF71F995FF63F945" box="[151,223,1640,1666]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FEF0F995FD5FF945" authority="Lundblad, 1936" authorityName="Lundblad" authorityYear="1936" box="[278,739,1640,1666]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epimeratus">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FEF0F995FD9FF946" box="[278,547,1640,1665]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesides epimeratus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B1DFF8BFFA6FDCCF995FD5FF945" author="Lundblad" box="[554,739,1640,1666]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" refString="Lundblad, O. (1936) Dritte Mitteilung uber Wassermilben aus Santa Catharina in Sudbrasilien. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 116, 200 - 211." type="journal article" year="1936">
Lundblad, 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FD4EF995FD5FF945" box="[680,739,1640,1666]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1936.0">1936</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F367767CFF8BFFA6FCCCF995FC1DF945" box="[810,929,1640,1666]" name="Colombia" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. However, all these taxa differ significantly from 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FF3DF972FE27F96F" box="[219,411,1679,1704]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Orientilimnesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FF3DF972FE27F96F" box="[219,411,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Orientilimnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2375785FF8BFFA6FE45F973FDA8F96F" box="[419,532,1678,1704]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the arrangement of acetabula. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FC35F972FBE1F96F" box="[979,1117,1679,1704]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FC35F972FBE1F96F" box="[979,1117,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FB7CF972FAB6F96F" box="[1178,1290,1679,1704]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FB7CF972FAB6F96F" box="[1178,1290,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the second acetabulum is located between the first and the third one or, in some case, at the same level as the third one (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FF03F921FD38F931" authority="Viets, 1935" authorityName="Viets" authorityYear="1935" box="[229,644,1756,1782]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="papillosa">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FF03F921FE5DF932" box="[229,481,1756,1781]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia papillosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B1DFF8BFFA6FE0CF921FD38F931" author="Viets" box="[490,644,1756,1782]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" refString="Viets, K. (1935) Die Wasermilben von Sumatra, Java und Bali nach den Ergebnissen der Deutschen Limnologischen Sunda-Expedition. Archiv fur Hydrobiologie, Supplement, 13, 484 - 738." type="journal article" year="1935">
Viets, 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FDA6F921FD38F931" box="[576,644,1756,1782]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1935.0">1935</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the adults were reported by Lundblad in 
<number id="3DB824CBFF8BFFA6FB57F921FB4AF931" box="[1201,1270,1756,1782]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1971.0">1971</number>
), whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D6FFF8BFFA6FF71F8FEFEF3F8DB" box="[151,335,1795,1820]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Orientilimnesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAFEFF8BFFA6FF71F8FEFEF3F8DB" box="[151,335,1795,1820]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Orientilimnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the second acetabulum is posterior to and underneath the third one.
</paragraph>
